{
    "analysis": "We have computed global thresholds (P95/P5) across full series and filtered the incident window. The metric scan produced a clear top candidate: the user service's diskio shows a very large breach (severity_high ≈ 13.4, max_in_window 86120.12 vs global_p95 6428.40) with earliest high at 2024-01-20T23:25:00Z. Several other services (queue-master diskio, many services' CPU) show modest high spikes (~1.02–1.55× P95) with earliest high around 23:26–23:40. Log analysis is less useful for error counts (thresholds = 0) but log.row_count spikes confirm short bursts of traffic or processing. According to the diagnosis rules, the root cause component must be among the service-level candidates (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user). The 'user' service is among these and exhibits an extreme disk I/O fault that is much larger than other deviations and therefore is the leading root-cause candidate. However, before finalizing we must verify that the user-diskio anomaly forms a contiguous fault (consecutive anomalous points) rather than isolated noisy spikes and check if other candidate KPIs show concurrent faults that could be the actual root cause. Thus the next atomic step is to inspect the in-window time series (timestamped values) for a small set of top candidates and mark which points exceed global P95 or fall below P5 so we can identify consecutive faults and the precise first faulty timestamp.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For these candidate component-KPIs: user/diskio, queue-master/diskio, rabbitmq-exporter/cpu, carts/cpu, orders/cpu, user/cpu — parse metric.csv (timestamps as pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True)). For each candidate compute its global_p95 and global_p5 from the full series (not filtered). Then filter points to the incident window 2024-01-20 23:22:07 UTC — 2024-01-20 23:52:07 UTC inclusive. Return for each candidate a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p5, timestamp (ISO UTC), value, is_high (value >= global_p95), is_low (value <= global_p5). Limit the output to these candidates only and show all in-window rows for each (expected ≤25 per candidate). Also return for each candidate the earliest timestamp where is_high is True (or null) and the count of consecutive high sequences (i.e., number of separate contiguous runs of is_high==True). Keep outputs concise and structured." }

Review: Metrics and log analysis identified a dominant, contiguous, and extreme disk I/O spike on the user service starting at 2024-01-20T23:25:00Z (user/diskio exceeded global P95 by ~13×). Other anomalies are smaller or later. Therefore the root cause is the user service with storage I/O saturation.

